 and qualities, 92, 93; enthusiasm in the study of the law, 93, 94,109, 111; lawyers' common-place book, 94; moot-court cases, 94; second Bowdoin prize, 95, 114, 115; librarian of Law School, 91, 96; prepares a catalogue, 96; contributor to the American Monthly Review, 96, 120; and to the American Jurist, 97; improvement in style, 97; character of his mind, 98; letters of classmates, 98-100; president of a temperance society, 101; member of a debating society, 101; delight in Fanny Kemble's acting, 101, 102; social visits in Cambridge, 102; recollections of him as a law student, by Mrs. Waterston, Rev. S. M. Emery, Professor W. C. Russell, and W. W. Story, 102-107, letters to classmates 1831-1833, 108– 122; death of his sister Matilda, 113, 114; dedication of Dane Hall, 116; religious belief, 117-119; Professor Ashmun's death, 119; Mr. Greenleaf's appointment, 119; completes law studies in office of Benjamin Rand, 123; contributes, while a student, to the Jurist, 123, 124; journey to Washington, 124, 125, 129, 130, 132– 134; calls at New York on Chancellor Kent, 131, 132; makes the acquaintance at Washington of Dr. Lieber, Henry Wheaton, and Richard Peters, 125; recollections by Miss Peters, 126, 127; hears arguments in the Supreme Court, 135, 136, 140; attends debates in Congress, and hears Webster, Clay, and Calhoun, 137,143; introduced to the floor of the Senate by Mr. Webster, 137; dislike of politics, 140-142; visit in Philadelphia, 126; declines a connection with the Law School, 127; serves as guard in defence of Harvard College, 128; admission to the bar, 129; letters, 1834, 129-145; early practice as a lawyer, 146; partnership with G. S. Hillard, 147, 148; lawyers at No. 4 Court Street, 147; II. 251; characteristics and rank in his profession, i. 149; instructor in the Law School, 149, 150, 187,188; appointed reporter of Judge Story's decisions, 150; assists Professor Greenleaf on a Digest, 150;
editor of American Jurist, 151, 152; edits Dunlap's Admiralty Practice, 152, 153; interest in codification, 153, 188, 189, 195; writes for the North American Review, 153; reads lectures before lyceums, 154; no promise of distinction as an orator, 154; unfortunate investment, 155; journey to Niagara and Canada, in 1836, 155, 156, 177-185; early interest in the slavery question, 156; relations with Rev. Dr. W. E. Channing, 157; correspondence with law writers, 157, 158; friendship with Dr. Lieber, 158-160; foreign correspondence, 160, 161; the Five of Clubs, 161; first acquaintance with Dr. Samuel G. Howe, 162; friendship with Richard Fletcher and Horace Mann, 162; social fellowships in Boston and Cambridge, 163-165; interest in young students, 165, 166; II. 322; letters, 1835-1837, i. 167-195; going to Europe, purpose of journey, letters of introduction, fears and good wishes of friends, 196– 203; letters before sailing, 204-212; voyage, 213-217; Havre, 217-219; Rouen, 220-224; Rouen to Paris, 224, 225; Paris, its schools, courts, professors, social life, entertainments, 226-297; leaves Paris for London, 297, 314; sketch of English visit, 298– 311; first weeks in London, courts, Parliament, Queen's coronation, society, literary men, 312-340; the circuits, visits to Cornwall, Chester, Liverpool, 341-344; visit to Robert Ingham, 344; speech at Newcastle, at meeting of the British Association for the Promotion of Science, 345-347; visit to Bishop of Durham at Auckland Castle, 347, 348; visit at Brougham Hall, 348-354; visit to John Marshall, 854; call on Wordsworth, 355, 356; visit to Sir David Brewster at Melrose, 357-359; intercourse with Lord Jeffrey, 359-361; visits in Scotland, 359-367; at Strachur Park (John A. Murray's), 365; visits in England, at Wortley Hall, Wentworth House, and Holkham House, 369-380; events at home, Dec. 1837—March, 1839, II. 1-3; letters of friends to him, 3-10; his letter on a child's death, 11, 12; visit to Boston, England, 12; dinner at 