314, 334; the national election in 1844, and his relation to the Whigs, 279, 280; enthusiasm for J. Q. Adams, 281; edits Vesey, Jr.'s, Reports, 282-286, 293; severe illness, 287-290, 309-319; death of his sister Mary, 291, 292, 321; professional work, the friction match case, 292. 293; interest in phrenology and animal magnetism, 294; scepticism as to the Brook Farm experiment, 294, 296; desire for marriage, 296; letters, 1844, 296– 323; interest in Horace Mann's work for popular education and assistance to Normal schools, 324-329; defeated as a candidate for the school committee, 324, 325; interest in the plan for
the new Boston Athenaeum, 329; attends annual meeting of the Prison Discipline Society, 329, 330,332, 334; correspondence, 330; letters, January to July, 1845, 331-336; his oration on The True Grandeur of Nations, July 4, 1845, an argument against war before the authorities of Boston, its distinctive character, the scene, extracts, criticism at the Faneuil Hall dinner, various opinions concerning it, its wide circulation and relation to his career, and his letters in reference to it, 340-384.
